cu500_pal | 1 | The waqf notation and the following words "the nineteenth" are written in the same ink, but the latter is in a different and larger hand.  The script is thuluth, fully pointed and voweled.  The decorative writing in the title panels represents markedly the mudghamah or assimilated type, in which certain connected letters are run together so as to render the point of ligature indistinct.  The final strokes of some of these letters are are frequently extended and/or curved so as to touch or overlap the following letter or letters.  The round or muqawwarah type, which requires both a curve and an incline in certain thuluth letters, is also much used.  The script of the text proper uses mostly the open or mabsutah stroke, that is, an almost rectilinear one extended out to a point in such letters as m, r, and w.  Thus, though the scripts of both the panels and the text are in thuluth, they present a different general appearance.  Every detail in the script as well as in the design shows very careful and exact workmanship.
cu500_rec | 1 | Source of description: On recto and verso: Qur&apos;an
cu500_t | 1 | Folio 1 is blank.  Folio 2a contains a waqf notation and the words "the nineteenth."  Folio 2b contains three lines of text from the beginning of juz&apos; 19 (Surah 25:21).  In the central cartouches of the panels on this page is the phrase from Surah 56:77-78, "Verily it is an honorable Qur&apos;an (written) in a preserved book."
